About Dataset

Context :This dataset is created specifically for learning and demonstrating customer segmentation using unsupervised machine learning—particularly, the K-Means Clustering algorithm.

Imagine you own a supermarket mall. Through membership cards, you’ve collected basic customer information such as:

Customer ID

Gender

Age

Annual Income (in $k)

Spending Score (assigned based on behavior and purchase history)

This project demonstrates how to use that data to identify distinct customer segments using K-Means in a simple and intuitive way.

Problem Statement

You want to understand your customers better and identify those who are more likely to respond to marketing efforts (your target customers). This insight can help the marketing team to:

Personalize marketing campaigns

Increase ROI

Focus on high-value segments

Objectives

By the end of this case study, you should be able to:

Perform customer segmentation using the K-Means Clustering algorithm in Python.

Identify target customer groups suitable for tailored marketing strategies.

Understand how customer segmentation contributes to real-world business decision-making.

🏷️ Source From :- AI/ML internship with Elevate Labs

Dataset: Mall_Customers.csv

Link :- https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/vjchoudhary7/customer-segmentation-tutorial-in-python

3. detect Outlines and Remove¶

In [19]:
for i in mall_Customer_data:
    q1 = mall_Customer_data[i].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = mall_Customer_data[i].quantile(0.75)
    
    iqr = q3-q1 
    
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    
    mall_Customer_data = mall_Customer_data[(mall_Customer_data[i] >= lower_bound) & ( mall_Customer_data[i] <= upper_bound)]

Step 3: Elbow Method to Find Optimal K¶

In [30]:
inertias = []
K_range = range(1, 11)

for k in K_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init="k-means++", random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(x_scaled)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot Elbow Curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(K_range, inertias, "bo-")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (K)")
plt.ylabel("Inertia")
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal K")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Interpretation: The "elbow" typically appears at K = 5, indicating a good cluster count.

Step 5: Evaluate Clustering Using Silhouette Score¶

In [31]:
score = silhouette_score(x_scaled, mall_Customer_data["Cluster"])
print(f"Silhouette Score: {score:.2f}")

Silhouette Score: 0.30

This is acceptable, but not very high. Here's how to interpret it:

Silhouette Score Interpretation

0.70 Strong structure (very good)

0.50 – 0.70 Reasonable structure (good)

0.30 – 0.50 Weak structure (okay)

< 0.30 No structure (poor)

So, 0.30 is borderline acceptable, meaning:

Clusters are not completely distinct, but there is still some separation.

It may help to experiment with feature selection or try PCA components or try other clustering methods like DBSCAN or Gaussian Mixture for improvement.
